result.execSummary:
The defendant Trevor Robert Rieck was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Bail Jumping-Felony, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(b).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Prosecuting attorney Erica Ellenwood in court for the State of Wisconsin. Includes 19CF377 (MH) & 22CF477(STC). Court reviews file and revocation of Deferred Judgment Prosecution Agreement filed by the State.  ADA Ellenwood states there is an agreement to withdraw request to revoke DPA and recites joint recommendation to close files today.  Court notes PH has not been held on 22CF477.  Atty Anderson states there will be a waiver on that file.  Court advises of rights and possible penalties regarding a preliminary hearing.  Court takes Judicial Notice of 19CF377 Court finds DF has freely, voluntarily, and knowingly waived the right to a preliminary hearing, finds probable cause that a felony was committed and the DF probably committed that felony and binds over for trial.  State to file information by end of business day today. Court continues with PLEAS. Court reads charge and maximum penalty. DE pleads G to Ct 1- Bail Jumping- Felony in 22CF477.  DE sworn. Crt reviews plea questionnaire and informs DE of rights. Crt finds DE freely, voluntarily and knowingly waives rights and makes plea. Attorney's stipulate to the facts. Crt accepts plea, finds factual basis and finds DE guilty of Ct 1 in 22CF377.  On motion of the State without objection, Crt dismisses Ct 2 & 3 in 22CF477 and outright dismiss 19CF377 as state has withdrawn motion to revoke DPA.  Sentencing arguments.  After a year and half, if DE stays in compliance with probation and completes all programing, Court will consider early discharge.
